# SuperClaim.ai - Cursor Rules

SuperClaim.ai is a multi-tenant B2B SaaS platform for AI-powered warranty claims
processing for electronics and gadgets. Brands sign up, configure claim policies,
manage a device registry, generate API keys, and use an isolated dashboard.

## PLATFORM SHAPE
Three planes share one tenant-isolated Postgres database:
1. CONTROL PLANE (FastAPI): auth, tenant management, policy CRUD, device registry,
   API key management. Accessed by brand users via JWT-authenticated dashboard.
2. DATA PLANE (FastAPI + Celery): the claims engine. POST /v1/claims/analyze,
   authenticated by API key id + secret (NOT JWT). Tenant is resolved FROM the key.
3. BRAND DASHBOARD (Next.js 14 App Router): each brand's isolated workspace.

## ABSOLUTE TENANCY RULE
Every table has tenant_id (except `tenants`). EVERY query MUST be filtered by
tenant_id via a FastAPI dependency layer. No endpoint may ever return cross-tenant
data. For the Data Plane, resolve the tenant from the authenticated API key -
NEVER trust a client-supplied X-Tenant-ID header. Cross-tenant isolation tests are
mandatory: prove tenant A cannot access tenant B's data.

## TECH STACK (DO NOT DEVIATE)
- Backend: FastAPI (Python 3.11+), SQLAlchemy 2.0 async, Alembic
- Database: Supabase managed Postgres via SUPABASE_DB_URL (use the IPv4 pooler host
  on Railway; the direct db.<ref>.supabase.co host is IPv6-only). Treat as plain
  Postgres; do NOT rely on Supabase RLS - tenancy is enforced in FastAPI.
- Vector: pgvector on Supabase (duplicate detection phase 2)
- Storage: Supabase Storage, PRIVATE bucket, path {tenant_id}/{claim_id}/{filename},
  signed URLs
- Queue: Celery + Redis
- Vision AI: GPT-4o Vision (behind a provider abstraction)
- OCR: Mistral Document AI behind an OCRProvider abstraction (OCR_PROVIDER env var)
  so PaddleOCR can replace it later without touching other services
- Fraud ML: LightGBM (rule-based fallback when model file is absent)
- Duplicate: imagehash (pHash) phase 1
- Dashboard: Next.js 14 + Tailwind + shadcn/ui
- Auth (dashboard): JWT access + refresh tokens, Argon2 password hashing
- Auth (Data Plane): API key (public key_id) + secret (Argon2-hashed, shown once)

## DATA MODEL (core tables, all with tenant_id except tenants)
tenants(id, name, slug, status, plan_tier)
users(id, tenant_id, email, password_hash, role[owner|admin|reviewer], status)
api_credentials(id, tenant_id, key_id, secret_hash, label, scopes[], status,
  last_used_at, expires_at)
policies(id, tenant_id, name, version, status[draft|active|archived], rules_json,
  effective_from, created_by)
devices(id, tenant_id, serial_number, device_category, device_model, purchase_date,
  warranty_months, customer_ref, batch_id, source)
claims(id, tenant_id, external_claim_id, device_id, policy_id, status, decision,
  confidence_score, fraud_score, requires_review, payload_json, result_json,
  ai_cost_usd)
claim_events(id, tenant_id, claim_id, event_type, actor, detail_json)
usage_records(id, tenant_id, period, claims_processed, ai_cost_total,
  billable_amount)

## POLICY ENGINE RULES (deterministic, NO AI/LLM)
Stored as rules_json, edited via UI. Evaluable rules, each returns
{ rule_id, passed, reason }:
- warranty_active: purchase_date + warranty_months > claim_date
- device_covered: device_category in covered_categories
- damage_covered: damage_type not in exclusions
- claim_limit: prior approved claims for serial < max_claims
- cooling_period: claim_date - purchase_date > cooling_days
- deductible: applied per claim if configured
Policies are versioned; only one active version per policy. Log every rule fired.

## CORE API CONTRACTS
Data Plane (API key auth):
  POST /v1/claims/analyze
  Headers: X-API-Key-Id, X-API-Secret
  Body: { external_claim_id, device_category, serial_number_input, purchase_date,
    claim_date, damage_description, images[], policy_id?, metadata{} }
  Response: ClaimAnalysisResult (see app/schemas/results.py)
Control Plane (JWT auth): /api/auth/*, /api/policies*, /api/devices*,
  /api/credentials*, /api/claims*, /api/team*, /api/usage

## CODING STANDARDS
- Pydantic v2 schemas; SQLAlchemy 2.0 async
- Every service & endpoint has tests in /tests, including cross-tenant isolation tests
- FastAPI Depends for: current_user (JWT), current_tenant_from_apikey (Data Plane),
  require_role
- Structured errors: { error_code, message, detail }
- Env via pydantic-settings; never hardcode secrets
- Secrets/passwords: Argon2. API secret shown once, stored hashed
- Type hints everywhere; avoid Any unless unavoidable
- All AI providers (vision, ocr) behind abstractions for later self-host swap

## COMPATIBILITY & VALIDATION RULES (NEVER VIOLATE)

### Single source of truth
1. ALL shared data shapes live in app/schemas/ as Pydantic v2 models. No service
   invents its own dict shape - it imports the canonical schema. If a field must
   change, change it in app/schemas/ and update every consumer in the same session.
2. ALL field names are snake_case everywhere (DB, Python, JSON API). Never camelCase
   in backend. The Next.js dashboard maps to camelCase only at its own boundary.
3. The canonical claim result schema is ClaimAnalysisResult in app/schemas/results.py.
   Every service writes into a sub-part of it; decision_service reads the whole
   thing. Do NOT create parallel/duplicate result shapes.

### Shared dependencies (fixed names - do not rename)
4. Auth dependencies have FIXED names (target home: app/core/security.py):
   - get_current_user        -> JWT user (Control Plane)
   - get_current_tenant      -> tenant from JWT user
   - get_tenant_from_apikey  -> tenant from API key + secret (Data Plane)
   - require_role(role)       -> role guard
   Every endpoint imports these - never redefine or rename them.
   NOTE (current state): the Data Plane today uses get_authenticated_context in
   app/security.py with X-API-Key + X-Tenant-ID. The API key + secret model
   (get_tenant_from_apikey) and app/core/ move are introduced in the auth session;
   until then, do not invent a third auth path.
5. The tenant-isolation query helper is tenant_query(model, tenant_id) (target home:
   app/core/database.py). Every data access uses it once introduced. Never write a
   raw query without tenant filtering.

### Service interface contract
6. Every *_service.py exposes ONE async entrypoint with a typed signature returning
   a canonical schema from app/schemas/results.py:
   - vision_service.analyze(image_url, device_category) -> VisionResult
   - ocr_service.extract(image_url) -> OCRResult
   - duplicate_service.check(tenant_id, claim_id, images) -> DuplicateResult
   - policy_engine.evaluate(policy, claim) -> PolicyResult
   - fraud_service.score(features) -> FraudResult
   - decision_service.decide(...all results...) -> ClaimAnalysisResult
   Signatures are FIXED - if you need more input, add an OPTIONAL field to the input
   schema (ClaimInput / ClaimFeatures), do not change the signature.
   NOTE (current state): existing services use legacy names (analyze_claim_image,
   extract_serial_from_image, analyze_duplicates_and_exif, evaluate_policy,
   score_fraud, build_decision) and legacy schemas (decision.py, vision.py, etc).
   Migrate each service to its canonical entrypoint + results.py types in its
   dedicated session; keep legacy functions until all callers move.

### Before writing new code each session
7. FIRST read app/schemas/results.py, app/security.py (and app/core/* once it
   exists), and app/database.py to reuse existing names/shapes. Do NOT invent new
   versions of things that already exist.
8. After writing code, run python scripts/check_compat.py and fix every ERROR
   (review WARNINGS) BEFORE considering the task done.

### Versioning & migration safety
9. Any DB model change requires a NEW Alembic migration in alembic/versions/ in the
   same session. Never edit an existing migration that may have run. Never change a
   column type without a migration.
10. API responses are additive-only after v1 is set: you may ADD optional fields,
    never remove or rename existing ones (the dashboard depends on them).

## END-OF-SESSION CHECKLIST
1. Confirm you used the canonical schemas in app/schemas/results.py (no duplicates).
2. Confirm you used the fixed dependency names (current_user/tenant, apikey, role).
3. Write/update unit tests for what you built, including a cross-tenant isolation test.
4. Run: python scripts/check_compat.py  - fix all ERRORS, review WARNINGS.
5. Run: pytest  - all tests must pass.
6. Run: ruff check . && mypy app/  - fix type and lint issues.
7. Summarize what changed and which schemas/dependencies you touched.

## DEPLOY NOTES (Railway)
- API service runs uvicorn; Worker service name must contain "worker" (auto-starts
  Celery via scripts/docker-entrypoint.sh). Dashboard is the Next.js app in dashboard/.
- REDIS_URL must be the Railway private Redis URL (never localhost in production).
- SUPABASE_DB_URL must use the Supavisor pooler host (IPv4), user
  postgres.<project_ref>; the direct host is IPv6-only and fails on Railway.
